<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-02-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-02-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="188" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d188">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">511.3B1/20</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The British Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lindsay</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-02-25"><hi rend="italic">February 25,
                                    1920</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 123</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: By direction of my Government I have the
                            honour to inform you that in reply to a request from the Belgian
                            Government, His Majesty’s Government have expressed the view, with
                            regard to aircraft under the Arms Traffic Convention, that if these are
                            not fitted or supplied with guns or bombs, bombing apparatus or
                            ammunition, they are free from the restrictions imposed by the
                            Convention, even if they are intended for observation use in
                            wartime.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">R. C. Lindsay</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>